@startuml
title Compact Fallbacks - Staying Safe When Compact Itself Fails

skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam dpi 130
skinparam defaultFontName Georgia
skinparam defaultFontSize 14
skinparam TitleFontSize 19
skinparam TitleFontColor #161616
skinparam NoteFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowColor #5E5A53
skinparam state {
  BackgroundColor #F2E9D9
  BorderColor #1D1D1D
  FontColor #161616
  ArrowColor #5E5A53
  StartColor #8C2721
  EndColor #161616
}
skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #F5EBDD
  BorderColor #8C2721
  FontColor #7B1E1E
}

[*] --> Start

state "Compact requested" as Start
state "Session-memory path" as Session #EFE6D8
state "Build summary request" as BuildSum
state "PTL hit?" as PTL <<choice>>
state "Trim oldest history\nretry summary" as Trim
state "Attempts counter" as Attempts #F5EBDD
state "Circuit breaker?" as Breaker <<choice>>
state "Restore critical\nfiles / skills / deltas" as Restore #EFE6D8
state "Next turn with\ncompact boundary" as Resume #E8DDD0
state "Stop auto-compact\nreturn control to caller" as Stop #F5EBDD

Start --> Session : session memory\nsufficient
Session --> Resume
Start --> BuildSum : needs summarization
BuildSum --> PTL
PTL --> Trim : yes
Trim --> Attempts
Attempts --> Breaker
Breaker --> Trim : attempts left
Breaker --> Stop : repeated failures
PTL --> Restore : no
Restore --> Resume
Resume --> [*]
Stop --> [*]

note right of Breaker
  Even compact can fail.
  A circuit breaker on
  retries prevents the loop
  from spiraling forever;
  control is handed back
  to the caller instead.
end note

@enduml
